It is not easy to reduce this sum of three hundred pence to its proper sense; partly because a penny was two- sold, a silver penny, and a gold one: partly because there was a double value and estimation of money, namely, that of Jerusalem and that of Tyre‚ as we observed before. Let these be silver (which we believe), which are of much less value than gold: and let them be Jerusalem pence (which we also believe), which are cheaper than the Tyrian3 yet they plainly speak the great wealth of Magdalene, who poured out an ointment of such a value, when before she had spent some such other.
